blockStates.name: Rayleigh–Bénard Convection
blockStates.userText:
The Bénard–Rayleigh convection is a type of 
natural convection that occurs in a layer of fluid 
when it is heated from below. Due to the effect of 
thermal buoyancy driven by the temperature 
difference, the convection results in a steady 
flow and a cellular pattern that is known as the 
Bénard cells.

The Bénard–Rayleigh convection can be 
simulated using the convection–diffusion equation 
introduced previously. This page shows the visual 
code for the simulation. The velocity field assumes
analytic forms as defined by the functions f(x,y)
and g(x,y). In a full-blown computational fluid
dynamics simulation, the velocity field is coupled
with the temperature field and should be computed 
alongside.

The example also shows that you can create a 
rectangular box that has different grid points in x
and y directions (NX and NY), not just a square box 
that has identical NX and NY, for a simulation. 
You may also use different steplengths DX and DY 
in different directions. 

Boundary conditions are critical in setting up this
simulation. Dirichlet's boundary is used to create the 
vertical temperature gradient, whereas Neumann's 
boundary is used to ensure the periodicity in the 
horizontal direction.
